explanation:
- OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro is invoked at the top of the function. To decide if its operations are dead you must know its expansion (does it perform logging, modify state, call OS_printf, or do an early return). If it expands to a no-op in some builds then those operations could be dead; if it has side effects then they are not dead.
- OS_ObjectIdFindByName: The function call is the primary operation of the target. Determining whether removing that call would change behavior requires knowing all its observable effects (return value semantics and whether it writes *sem_id, performs logging, or alters global state).
- LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE: The constant/type passed into OS_ObjectIdFindByName can change the function’s behavior and side effects; its value or compile-time mapping can affect whether the call produces observable effects.
- OS_ObjectIdGetByName and OS_ObjectIdRelease: These are callees of OS_ObjectIdFindByName (per the static graph). To fully assess the side effects of OS_ObjectIdFindByName (and therefore whether that call is removable/dead), the internals of these helpers must be known.
- OS_printf: Appears in the call graph (likely used by the macro or the called functions). I/O/logging is an observable side effect; if any removed operation only affects logging then it is not dead. Must know whether and how OS_printf is invoked.
- osal_id_t (definition): The actual type/qualifiers of sem_id (e.g., volatile, pointer-to-volatile, or containing side-effecting semantics) determine whether writes to *sem_id are observable; this affects whether the assignment inside the called function is removable.
- int32 (definition): Confirm whether the return type has any qualifiers (e.g., volatile) or special semantics that would make the local assignment/return observable.
- Return-code constants (e.g. OS_SUCCESS, OS_INVALID_POINTER): Knowledge of the concrete return codes and their use in callers is needed to judge whether removing the function call or pointer-checks would change externally observable behavior (different error codes returned).
